Sama Amr Habib - Data analysis¶

Digital wallet transaction¶

Dataset Description¶

Digital Wallet Transactions dataset contains details of digital financial activities for a digital wallet platform, with 5000 synthetic records covering last year. The dataset spans various features reflecting real-world digital wallet functionalities. With dynamic transaction dates, it provides an excellent foundation for analyzing spending patterns, evaluating cashback effectiveness, and exploring seasonal trends in digital wallet usage. This dataset is ideal for uncovering insights into user behavior, merchant popularity, and potential fraud detection.

Kaggle Dataset Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/harunrai/digital-wallet-transactions

Overview:¶

This dataset simulates transactions from a digital wallet platform similar to popular services like PayTm in India or Khalti in Nepal. It contains 5000 synthetic records of various financial transactions across multiple categories, providing a rich source for analysis of digital payment behaviors and trends.

Potential Use Cases¶

Analyzing spending patterns across different product categories Studying the effectiveness of cashback and loyalty programs Investigating the relationship between payment methods and transaction success rates Exploring seasonal trends in digital wallet usage Developing fraud detection models based on transaction patterns Segmenting users based on their spending behavior Analyzing the popularity of different merchants and services

#Highest number of transaction by users

warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=FutureWarning, module="seaborn")

UserIDTransactions = df.groupby('UserID')['TransactionID'].count()
UserIDTransactions = UserIDTransactions.astype(int)

TransactionCounts = UserIDTransactions.value_counts().reset_index()
TransactionCounts.columns = ['Number of Transactions', 'Number of Users']
TransactionCounts = TransactionCounts.sort_values(by='Number of Transactions')

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(data=TransactionCounts, x='Number of Transactions', y='Number of Users', color='#4682B4')
plt.title('Highest number of Transactions')
plt.xlabel('Number of Transactions')
plt.ylabel('Number of Users')

plt.show()
  1. Transaction Over time shows significant daily fluctuations in transaction volume, with no clear seasonal trend.
  2. Urban users have the most transactions, which can help target marketing efforts or expansion plans.
  3. Urban Users have the highest number of transactions in categories like Streaming Service, and Hotel Booking
  4. Most transactions have been performed using Android. Hence android users would weigh higher when introducing new app features.
  5. Transaction Health Status tells us about 95% Successful Transactions, 3% Pending, and 2% Failed.
  6. Python Programming Course is the leading Product purchase, this could be due to a seasonal trend.
  7. Consumer prefered products include a mix of both necessity payments and recreational purchases, no specific trend.
  8. Airbnb, Flipkart and MakeMyTrip are the leading Merchants by the revenue and volume both,which indicated the potential marketing or partnership efforts
  9. Payment Method Preference has no significant difference in the payment method utilization.
  10. User Product Category Preferences do not really give any visible pattern, indicating inconsistent useage.
  11. Highest number of transactions:
    1. 77.03% users made 1 transaction.
    2. 19.30% users made 2 transactions.
    3. 3.13% users made 3 transactions.
    4. 0.54% users made 4 transactions.
